H.B. 689
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
Apr 1, 2025
SESSION 2025
HOUSE PRINCIPAL CLERK
H D
HOUSE BILL DRH10295-MT-13
Short Title: Expanding Workforce and Education Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Cervania.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO EXPAND NORTH CAROLINA'S WORKFORCE BY PROVIDING IN-STATE
3 TUITION TO NORTH CAROLINA HIGH SCHOOL GRADUATES WHO MEET
4 CERTAIN CRITERIA.
5 Whereas, a one percentage point (1%) increase in the postsecondary attainment rate
6 would have resulted in over five hundred million dollars ($500,000,000) in additional economic
7 growth for North Carolina over just one year according to the United States Bureau of Economic
8 Analysis; and
9 Whereas, over eighty percent (80%) of the State's employers reported difficulty in
10 finding employees for jobs requiring industry-valued credentials, and these high-skills jobs are
11 expected to increase by more than eleven percent (11%) in the next six years; and
12 Whereas, while North Carolina's employers report difficulty in finding skilled
13 employees, postsecondary enrollment for The University of North Carolina constituent
14 institutions and North Carolina community colleges has fallen on average by 2.7% since 2019;
15 and
16 Whereas, North Carolina must pursue multiple strategies to increase postsecondary
17 enrollment so the State can have more potential employees entering the workforce with
18 industry-valued credentials; Now, therefore,
19 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
20 SECTION 1. G.S. 116-143.1 is amended by adding the following new subsections
21 to read:
22 "(n) Notwithstanding any other provision of this section, a person who meets all of the
23 following qualifications shall be eligible to be charged the in-State tuition rate:
24 (1) The person graduated and received a high school diploma from a school
25 within North Carolina that is not a nonpublic residential school.
26 (2) The person enrolled in the institution of higher education in the school year
27 immediately following his or her graduation and receipt of a high school
28 diploma.
29 (3) The person attended North Carolina public or nonpublic schools for a
30 minimum of four consecutive years immediately prior to high school
31 graduation and receipt of a high school diploma.
32 (4) The person holds an unexpired North Carolina drivers license or special
33 identification card issued under G.S. 20-37.7.
34 (5) The person has received a social security number and card from the United
35 States Social Security Administration.
36 This subsection does not make a person a resident of North Carolina for any other purpose.
*DRH10295-MT-13*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (o) A person who is eligible to be charged the in-State tuition rate as provided in
2 subsection (n) of this section shall provide evidence of his or her unexpired North Carolina
3 drivers license or special identification card at the beginning of each semester of enrollment to
4 continue to be eligible to be charged the in-State tuition rate.
5 (p) Any information obtained as part of the process of applying for the in-State tuition
6 rate pursuant to subsection (n) or (o) of this section shall be confidential and is not a public
7 record."
8 SECTION 2. G.S. 116-143.4 reads as rewritten:
9 "§ 116-143.4. Admissions status of persons charged in-State tuition.
10 (a) A person eligible for the in-State tuition rate pursuant to this Article shall be
11 considered an in-State applicant for the purpose of admission; provided that, admission.
12 However, a person eligible for in-State tuition pursuant to G.S. 116-143.3(c) shall be considered
13 an in-State applicant for the purpose of admission only if at the time of seeking admission he the
14 person is enrolled in a high school located in North Carolina or enrolled in an adult high school
15 equivalency diploma program in an institution located in this State.
16 (b) A person eligible for the in-State tuition rate pursuant to G.S. 116-143.1(n) shall not
17 be considered an in-State applicant for the purposes of admission to a constituent institution of
18 The University of North Carolina."
19 SECTION 3. This act becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies beginning with
20 the 2025-2026 academic year.
